🌿 Ayurvedic Classification of Skin & Its Modern Relevance

Ayurveda, the ancient Indian science of healing, views skin health as a reflection of inner well-being rather than just external care.

{/* Grid Section */}
{/* Left Section */}

🔹 Why is Ayurvedic Skin Care Important Today?

  • ✅ Holistic Approach – Treats the root cause, not just symptoms.
  • ✅ Personalized Care – Different skin types (Vata, Pitta, Kapha) require different treatments.
  • ✅ Natural Healing – Uses herbs, oils, and diet instead of chemicals.
  • ✅ Long-Term Benefits – Prevents premature aging, acne, and dryness.
{/* Right Section */}

🌿 Traditional Ayurvedic Classification of Skin

Ayurveda describes skin using two major systems:

  • Charaka’s Two-Layer Model: Hydration (Udakdhara) and Blood Circulation (Asrukdhara).
  • Sushruta’s Seven-Layer Model: Includes layers for radiance, immunity, pigmentation, and healing.
{/* Second Grid */}

🌿 Ayurvedic Approach to Skin Types (Dosha-Based Care)

Ayurveda classifies skin into three types based on the dominant Dosha:

  • Vata (Dry & Thin Skin): Needs deep hydration with oils.
  • Pitta (Sensitive & Acne-Prone): Requires cooling herbs.
  • Kapha (Oily & Thick Skin): Benefits from detoxifying masks.

🌿 Ayurvedic Disease Correlations with Modern Dermatology
